assical theory: first-order equations, local existence theorems, and an extensive discussion of the fundamental differential equations of mathematical physics. The techniques of modern analysis, such as distributions and Hilbert spaces, are used wherever appropriate to illuminate these long-studied topics. The last three chapters introduce the modern theory: Sobolev spaces, elliptic boundary value problems, and pseudodifferential operators.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDifferential equations, Partial. 7aMATHEMATICS / Differential Equations / Partial.2bisacsh  aBessel function.  aCauchy data.  aDirichlet problem.  aFeynman propagator.  aGaussian kernel.  aHadamard example.  aLaplacian.  aLewy equation.  aNeumann problem.  aPoisson kernel.  aRellich's theorem.  aSobolev norm.  aSobolev space.  aadjoint.  aamplitude.  acotangent space.  aelliptic operator.  aheat operator.  amaximum principle.  anormal derivative.  aoriented hypersurface.  aparametrix.  aradial function.  awave operator.  aweak solution.1 aFolland, Gerald B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691213033zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691213033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691213033.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles